\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 F}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
aust's first impression was of a pearly grayness that suffused everything. That persisted only for a moment, however, as Spiritual Space accommodated itself to the novelty of having an earthly obser\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ver within it by expanding outwards on all sides. After that, Faust saw that he was standing just on the outskirts of a small city, very like in appearance to cities he had seen in his travels around Europe, though by no means identical.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 He had certainly g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
otten to this place very quickly. But that stood to reason, since the Spiritual Realm, having no substance except for that imposed by the temporary rules of Solidification, can be shrunk down to a tiny compass by Nature, which abhors a vacuum and isn't ab
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ut to leave a lot of unused space around, either. The learned doctors at the Jagiellonian taught that when the Spiritual Realm wasn't being used, it resided in a space no larger than a pinhead
\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to such an infinitesimal mass may the immaterial be reduced! T\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e only thing that would cause it to expand was the presence of an observer. Then the space created itself, with the sort of scenery and personnel as might be expected in this place and at this time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust entered the city and saw a row of storefronts. Abov\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e each was a sign. Faust could not decipher the lettering on them, by which he knew they were not for him to enter. At last he saw one sign that read, }{\cs18\scaps\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 'the witches' kitchen'}{\insrsid13440386 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 . And he knew that was the place he was to go to. (So much is inherent in the Trans\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
portation Spell, which takes you unerringly to the threshold of your next adventure, though you're on your own after that.)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust approached the Witches' Kitchen. He walked up to the door and touched it with a gingerly gesture. He had been afraid that his \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hand would pass through it, since only spirit is supposed to exist in such a place, and spirit is well known for its ability to pass through other spirits. But the door felt solid and a moment's reflection told him that even if a body in this place were n
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
t solid, it would have to act as though it were in order for anything to happen; for as the ancient philosophers have pointed out, there's no drama unless things can bump into each other. But how, being aethereal, had they managed to become solid? Faust d
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 cided that it must be because the entities here had taken a formal oath to maintain solidness despite the comforts of intangibility, and above all not to melt into each other.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust entered the Witches' Kitchen and saw a whole host of small demons of not v\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ery frightening aspect attending to a group of patrons who sat in chairs with striped sheets over their bodies. It seemed to be a beauty salon of some kind. These demons were evidently barbers, or surgeons, for not only did they cut hair, they also scallo
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ed away fat from obese bellies, trimmed beef from sausagelike thighs, and added strands of glistening red muscle to wasted arms and shrunken calves. They scrubbed dirt off the body and sandpapered blemishes out of the skin. Under their skilled claws, face
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  were reconstructed, the devils utilizing gobs of all-purpose flesh that they kept in vats beside their barber chairs.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In a moment, however, it became obvious that the demons were mere assistants. Walking among them, supervising, and themselves performing \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
the more delicate bits of reconstruction, were a dozen or so witches. They all wore the same ragged, rusty garments, and they had high peaked hats perched on their narrow heads, hats whose brims sloped uncannily over their glittering eyes. And they all ha
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  high lace-up boots around their skinny shanks, and most of them had a baleful black cat perched on a knobby shoulder.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, what's this?" said a senior witch, whose rank could be told by the black crepe rose she wore pinned to her hat. "Are you the basic\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 material package we requested? Step over here, dearie, and we'll have you dismembered in no time."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I am nobody's package," Faust said proudly. "I am Johann Faust, a doctor of the Earth Realm."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It seems to me we just had a person of that name passing thr\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ough here," the witch said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Was he accompanied by a tall, skinny demon named Mephistopheles?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Why, yes, he was, though he wasn't skinny to }{\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 my}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  tastes."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That man with him was not Faust! He was an impostor! I am Faust!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The witch looked at him levelly. "I \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 thought he was young to be a learned doctor! Do you have any identification?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust rummaged through his wallet (which had been transported and spiritualized but otherwise was the same as back on Earth) and found an honorary sheriff-ship from the town of L\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ublin, a voter's registration shard from Paris, and a silver commemorative medal awarded to him at the Great Fair of Thaumaturgy that had taken place two years past in Prague.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well then, you }{\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 are}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  Faust," the witch said. "And that other fellow deceived me, \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
and Mephistopheles, too, unless I miss my guess. It's too had. We gave him such a nice rejuvenation. You would have wept to see how beautiful we made him."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It was wrongly done!" Faust cried, gnashing his teeth. "Now you must do the same for me!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That wil\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l not be possible," the witch said. "We already used up most of the allotment for that rejuvenation. Still, let's see what we can do."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 She guided Faust to a chair. There she called over one of her demon assistants, and the two conferred in low voices.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "The\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  trouble is," the demon said, "we used up almost all the longevity serum on the other fellow."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Strain out the dregs and use them. They're better than nothing."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But his features!" The demon tilted Faust's head to one side and then to the other. His eyes, \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hard as agates, studied Faust's features and showed no sign of being impressed. "Lacking a beauty pack, what can I do with this gross, long-nosed, sunken-cheeked, thin-lipped, and ill-formed visage?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Hey!" Faust cried. "I didn't come here to be insulted!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
"Shut up," said the demon. "I'm the doctor here, not you." Turning to the witch, he said, "We could build up his physique, not to superhuman powers, of course, since that preparation hasn't come through, but to a respectable degree."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Do what you can," sa\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 id the witch.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
The demon worked swiftly and with an elan that frightened Faust until he perceived that the demon's ministrations didn't hurt. Then he relaxed in the chair while the demon, humming monotonously to himself, plucked away some of the more pendul
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ous portions of Faust's anatomy and molded fresh flesh in their place, holding the strips of dripping skin in place until they had hardened to the bone. Lastly he ran strands of nerve and muscle and sinew 'into the appropriate places so that Faust could s
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ile or grimace or move his limbs, and fixed them in place with small applications of Universal Fastener.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 He finished, trimmed off the final odds and ends, stepped back to study the result, and nodded sagely to himself, saying, "Better than I expected, give\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
n the materials I had to work with." Then he brushed Faust off, whisked off the striped sheet, and bade him look at himself in one of the tall wall mirrors.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust beheld in the glass a man rather more robust than he remembered himself. His skin had lost th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e waxy whiteness of old age and had taken on the ruddy hue of the middle years. His eyesight was improved, too, as well as his hearing. His features were still recognizably his own, but the demon had fined down his rather peremptory nose, brought out his 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hin a bit, and taken away his dewlaps. All in all he was a better-looking man than before, though he was still not likely to win one of the male beauty contests that were held secretly in some parts of Italy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It's better," Faust admitted, studying himself\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  in the mirror, "but it's still not good enough. It is my right to have the full rejuvenation treatment!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The demon shrugged and turned away. The witch said, "Let us not speak of rights. We gave you this much out of the goodness of our hearts. Never say th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
at witches are all bad! For the full works, you will have to get a requisition slip signed by Mephistopheles himself, or one of the other great princes of Light or Dark. Only then can we requisition the materials from Central Supply."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'll get that," Faus\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t said, "and a lot else besides. Where did Mephistopheles say he was going next?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "He didn't mention it to us."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "In what direction did he decamp?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Straight up in the air, in a cloud of fire and smoke, as is his wont."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust knew that he could not do that.\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 His Transportation Spell was too limited. It had brought him to this place, but it had not the power to carry him further. He would have to return to Earth and make his plans.
