\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 I}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t was a disconsolate Faust who rematerialized inside the pentagram\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 chalked on the floor of his chambers. Coming from the workmanlike bustle of the Witches' Kitchen, his own quarters struck him as unbearably shabby and forlorn. That damned servant girl hadn't even dusted his skeleton! And his cloaks were still mud-caked 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 rom the spring rains. There were going to be some changes around here, he decided. He gnashed his teeth.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 This was what came of being nice to people: impostors without even a casual knowledge of alchemy thought they could come in and steal your long-awaited\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 pact with the devil. Like hell they could! He'd show them!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Meanwhile, there was his rejuvenation to consider. He noticed that he seemed to have a lot more energy than before. His irascible nature, which had begun to soften with age, returned now with a ru\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
sh. Damn it, he was Faust! He was strong! And he was hungry!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 He turned to his pantry. There on the top shelf was his bowl of porridge, a goodly lot of it left over from last night's cooking. He stirred it with his long spoon. It had lumps in it, and was th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e color of corpse fat. His newly rejuvenated digestion told him he couldn't tolerate that stuff any longer. Especially now that the witch at the Witches' Kitchen had thoughtfully given him a fine set of teeth, as good as new except for a chip in the left 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ncisor. He didn't want porridge! He wanted meat! And revenge, revenge!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Without further ado he left his room, went down the stairs, and out into the street. It was evening now, a blue and delightful evening, fit consort of the fabulous Easter day. Faust pai\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
d it no heed. He had better things to do than sing strophes to the weather! He crossed the street and clumped into the tavern he frequented.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Landlord!" he cried. "I'll have a slice of your roast suckling pig, and don't be stingy with the crackling!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 andlord was surprised to see this sudden change of humor in the usually sober and morose-sounding Faust. But he merely enquired, "Barley and groats on the side, sir?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "No groats, damn it, I'll have a full serving of Polish fried potatoes instead. And have \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 the serving wench fetch me a pitcher of decent wine, not that wretched, thin Polack red."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Tokay okay?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Yes, and Rhine's fine, too, just hurry up and bring it."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Faust took a table apart from the common customers, for he wanted to think. The tavern was sha\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
dowy, with a small fire in the big hearth. There were tallow wicks burning on a wagon wheel overhead. It rocked ever so slightly from its long chains set into the ceiling beam due to the draft that blew in through the ill-made door. A serving girl brought
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
his wine, and Faust quaffed half a pint without looking up. The girl soon reappeared with his slice of pork on a wooden trencher, with an oily heap of Polish fried potatoes on the side, and even a little plate of spiced red cabbage. Faust's stomach would 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
