\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "On the shore outside Constantinople," said Mephistopheles, "close to \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 the Frankish encampment. This is where I will leave you. Are you ready for your instructions?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That I am," Mack said, trying to put a good face on it but wishing that he had a cup of wine to buck him up. "What do you want me to do?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You have three choice\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s," Mephistopheles said. "We require you to pick one."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And what are these choices?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "One, to kill Henry Dandolo. Two, to kidnap Alexius the Pretender. Three, to rescue the sacred icon of St. Basil."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack thought it was unfair, having to face so many choic\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
es before breakfast. But he knew he'd get no sympathy from the now stern-faced Mephistopheles, and so he said, "Which of those would you like me to perform?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "My likes and dislikes have nothing to do with this matter," Mephistopheles said. "You must use yo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ur own judgment."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But on what basis am I to decide?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You must come up with your own criteria, for this is an exercise in human judgment and free will."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Dandolo? Alexius? But I don't know those people!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Obviously, you must acquaint yourself with them."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And to kill a man\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that was one of my choices, was it not?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It was indeed."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, surely the forces of Good would take exception to that."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I think I can speak for my friend Archangel Michael," Mephistopheles said, "when I tell you that you give Good too\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 little credit if you think it never recognizes any grounds for killing. Good knows that there are worse things than that. Not that they condone killing in general; nor do we, for that matter, for intelligence and selection are the essence of both Good an
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 Evil. But none of us gets too worked up over it, being immortals as we are, and used to the long view. We know that killing is a matter of very great importance to men, and so we include its possibility in our contest. And I will also tell you this: In k
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 lling, the motive is everything, and the ends are to be considered as well as the means."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But how can I know the ends? How can I tell what the killing of this Dandolo will do in terms of future outcomes?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You face a problem common to all men. There is ne\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ver enough evidence to know whether to kill or not. Yet sometimes it must be done, both from the point of view of Light as well as that of Dark."

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'll be judged harshly if I make a mistake."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "No one will judge you but Ananke, Necessity, the judge of us al\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l. Choose you must. That is the role of a Faust."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, if you say so. Who am I supposed to kill again?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Henry Dandolo, the doge of Venice. And only if you decide that that's the best action under the circumstances."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And the other guy? Alex something?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Alexius, Pretender to the throne of Constantinople."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And the third choice again?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "To rescue the sacred relic of St. Basil, protector of Constantinople. Really, Faust, you must pull yourself together. You are well known for your tenacious memory."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It wo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 rks better when I don't have a hangover," Mack said. "Now would you just mind telling me what a Frankish army is doing at Constantinople?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mephistopheles raised an interrogative eyebrow. "I thought an educated man like yourself would know all about this mi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ghty event which took place only a few hundred years ago. I am surprised by your ignorance\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
though I also know this perhaps is but your bit of a joke. It is the Fourth Crusade, of course. But you must discover the situation for yourself, and take your best\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 action."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, I'll try," Mack said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You must do more than that," Mephistopheles said. "We have contracted with you to perform certain actions. If you fail to perform them in the time allotted, you will ruin our contest, and win for yourself something ra
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ther unpleasant."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And what would that be?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Pain unspeakable in an everlasting pit in the bottomless places of horror where you wilt be killed unspeakably and then brought back to life to be killed again, and again, and again, until we can thi
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 nk up something worse for you. You have twenty-four hours in which to perform your deed. Adieu."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 And with that Mephistopheles took to the air and soon vanished into the sky's sunny vastnesses.
