\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 M}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ack stayed for a while in the cove, turning things\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 over in his mind, until at last, deciding he had better get on with it, he began walking. He soon found himself on a vast plain that stretched, yellow and green, as far as the eye could see. A half mile ahead of him were the steep walls of Constantinople
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 .\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 These walls were higher and more massive than any he had seen in Europe. Sentries in brass cuirasses, with horsetail plumes on their bright helmets, marched along the battlements. Below, and a half mile back from the walls, there were hundreds of tents s
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
read around the plain, and a multitude of camp-fires, and great crowds of armed men. There were also many wagons camped a little apart, in a place of their own, with women and children around them. As he came closer, Mack could see that forges had been se
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 up, and smiths were even now hammering out arrowpoints and lance heads. There were other wagons from which provisions were being unloaded, and there were pavilions with brightly colored banners flying from lances set before them. These seemed to be the a
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
odes of the leaders of this great expedition. Mack saw that this place was a veritable traveling city, a place that could pack up and move at any time. He realized that this city must have been moving almost daily since the host had left Frankland.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 There w\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
as nothing to do but get on with it, and so he began walking toward the camp. As he approached, a group of horsemen rode by at a smart trot, and their leader raised a mailed hand to Mack, who waved in return. They must have mistaken him for one of the Fra
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
kish group, since his clothes were the good grays and browns and blacks of dear old Europe, not the gorgeous silks and satins of the fabulous East. He walked on, and soon he passed the first outliers, men-at-arms with lance and shield laid aside, reclinin
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  at their ease in the mild sunshine.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What news bring you of the council?" one of them called out.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What news I bring is not for your ears," Mack said, deciding to take a high hand lest he be undone at the very beginning.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But is Boniface of Montferrat sti\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ll at the meeting? That alone would be a sign of progress."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I can tell you this much," Mack said. "Conditions haven't changed much in the last few hours."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Then there's still hope of recovering honor out of this thieves' nest," another of the men-at-arms \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 muttered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Mack walked on. At last he came to a place that looked familiar. It was a wagon with a broad canopy to one side of it, and under that canopy there were chairs and tables, and there were hogsheads piled high, and men were sitting at the tables and
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  drinking and eating. It was a tavern on wheels.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Grateful that he had found a place at last where he could feel at home, Mack entered and found himself a seat.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The tavern keeper appeared, and, taking in the finery in which Mack had been clothed at the Witc\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 hes' Kitchen, louted low and said, "What might I bring you, my lord?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Your best wine," Mack said, realizing at once that his credit might be very good in this place.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The tavern keeper drew a piggin of wine and returned with it. "I have not seen you before\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , sir. Might it be that you have only recently joined our great company?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It might indeed be," Mack said. "Is that a roast of venison I smell on the back rack?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It is. My lord hath a discerning nose. I'll bring you a gobbet of it forthwith. Prithee, sir,\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  what can you tell us of any tidings you bring from your famous master?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What master is that?" Mack said, for the fellow's indirection left him grasping for the meaning, if any.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I simply assumed, sir, that so great a lord as yourself did no doubt serve a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 greater; for it is written that all things serve another in this world, whether villein to master, ox to farmer, lord to God, and so on through the heavenly ranks where the rule is the same."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Your loquacity is exceeded only by your perspicacity," Mack sa\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 id, the wine having bucked him up considerably.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "My lord, might I enquire your name?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I am Johann Faust."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And you have journeyed far to reach us?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Aye, passing far," Mack said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And tell me, sir, whom do you serve?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The loungers in the tavern craned for\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ward to catch the answer. But Mack merely smiled and said, "That is not for me to say at this time."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Couldn't you give us a hint, though?" For a small crowd, indeed, a half multitude, had gathered around while the tavern keeper and Mack were holding their\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  colloquy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The landlord squinted one eye and said, "I'll bet you're an agent of the Council of Venice, which seeks to instruct and restrain the vainglorious Henry Dandolo, doge of Venice."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack shrugged.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "No," cried another, "he's no man of the Venetians, \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
for note you not that look of proud piety on his face and how his hands seek his sleeves as if he were wearing a monk's habit? I'll bet he's a churchman in disguise, come from Innocent the Third, our Pope who organized this holy Crusade and now finds hims
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 lf thwarted by the machinations of the diabolical Henry Dandolo."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 They all stared at Mack, who said, "I wouldn't say yes and I wouldn't say no."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A third man, a soldier, declared, "It is apparent from his firm bearing and laconic replies that he is a soldie\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
r. No doubt he represents Philip of Swabia, a fighting man of few words, albeit many deeds that cry to Heaven for avenging. And I'll bet he brings an offer concerning who is to be ruler of Constantinople once the present incumbent, the inconvenient and st
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 bborn Alexius the Third, has been reduced to a blind beggar scuffling for scraps in the dustbins of his once haughty city."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack gave no hint as to his political leanings. There was much conversation about whom Mack was representing, for there seemed no do\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ubt that he was there on behalf of }{\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 someone}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
. The tavern keeper would accept no pay for his food and drink, asking instead that Mack remember him when the council met to regulate the use of strong drink among the Crusaders. And when Mack made to leave, a sho\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rt, plump, well-dressed young man in clerk's gray introduced himself as Wasyl of Ghent and asked permission to assist Mack in getting quarters, since he had neglected to do so hitherto.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 And so they walked together to the bright yellow double tent with the \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
pennons flying in front of it, for this was headquarters of the Quartermaster Corps. There were loungers at the flap, but Wasyl cleared them out of the way with his announcement, "Make way for Johann Faust, a visitor from Frankland, and one who has not as
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 yet announced his party and affiliation."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The quartermaster was impressed, and, asking no questions, assigned Mack to a high-peaked tent a little off to itself, since he had not associated himself with any of the factions. Wasyl, who seemed to have appoint
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ed himself servant and general factotum to Mack's certain but unspecified importance, went ahead to make sure that all was ready. When Mack arrived at his new quarters, he saw that a nice table had been laid for him, and there was a cold fowl and a bottle
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
of wine and a half loaf of good wheaten bread. Not scorning a second lunch, for the tavern keeper had been niggardly with his gobbet of venison, Mack tucked in, meanwhile listening to Wasyl prate of the affairs of the day.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Everyone agrees," Wasyl said, "t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hat Henry Dandolo, the doge of Venice, has turned what began as a religious matter into a thing of commerce. That is an advantage or a disadvantage depending on how you look at the rival priorities of religion and commerce." And he looked keenly at Mack t
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  see which way his sympathies lay. But Mack merely waved a drumstick and took another bite of bread.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Pope Innocent the Third," Wasyl went on, "is a pure man in his singleminded desire to free Jerusalem from the Saracen. Yet might not even his motives be s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
uspect due to his overweening desire to bring the Greek Christians under the rule of Rome?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Interesting point," Mack said, finishing the bread and starting on some candied sweetmeats he found near-by.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Then there is the question of Alexius the Fourth, as h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e is sometimes called, though as yet he has no kingdom, the son of the deposed Isaac the Second Angelus. They say he has promised to bring Constantinople under the sway of Rome if he becomes king. So he is seemingly allied to the side of piety. Yet it is 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 rue that his principal backing comes from Philip of Swabia, no friend to the Holy See, a violent man with ambitions as large as his domain is small."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I see what you mean," Mack said, though he was making little sense out of the dissertation.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And finally \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
we must consider the position of Villhardoin, leader of the military expedition, a man both feared and respected, respectful of religion but not himself pious. A good man, one might say. Yet Villhardoin is noted for the extreme shallowness of his politica
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  opinions and his indifference to commerce. All he cares about is the clash of edged weapons. Is he the man we need to lead us?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack wiped his mouth and looked around for a place in which to take a nap. The indispensable servant had provided a fine cot wi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 th comforter and newfangled pillow. Mack got up and walked toward it.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "My lord, I am your man," Wasyl said. "Will you not take me into your confidence, tell me who you favor and from whom you bring a message? I will fight and connive in your interests, lor\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
d. Do but tell me what they are."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack wished he could say, because he figured he needed people on his side in this contentious place. But he didn't know at this point what was the stronger party, nor on which side right lay, nor what he should do that wou
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ld further the progress of mankind and preserve the city of Constantinople.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Good servant," he said, "all will be vouchsafed to you in good time. Believe me, you will be the first to know where my sympathies lie. For now, go about the camp and see what rum\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ors are extant, and then come back to me in an hour or two."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I go!" Wasyl said, and left. Mack stretched out and was asleep almost immediately.
