\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 M}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ar\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
guerite couldn't believe it. She had always heard that magicians were a fickle lot, but this, in the old German expression, really took the apple kuchen. She had gone from a tavern in Cracow to a cell in Constantinople, and she didn't even know what she'd
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
been arrested for. And here she was, abandoned by Faust and probably in a lot of trouble. She paced up and down the cell, then cowered back as she heard the sound of heavy footsteps marching down the passageway. The footsteps stopped, the door to the next
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 cell clanged open.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Marguerite waited, listening. There was a brief pause. Then the steps started up again. They stopped in front of her cell. She heard the sound of a key rattling in the crude lock. Then the lock turned. She cowered as the door to her cell
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  swung open.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
And saw, entering the doorway, a tall, yellow-haired young fellow dressed in fine clothing. He paused in the doorway, looking at her with a gaze of some attentiveness. For a while the two of them formed a tableau there in the gray light that f
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
iltered into the cell from the guttering horn lanterns hung in the corridor. The newcomer was little more than a boy with a sheen of perspiration dappling his upper lip, staring, while she, her long, chestnut hair tangled in an attractive way, long skirt 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 lightly raised to show her attractive ankles, cowered in a posture most pathetic yet most enticing, too.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Then Mack, for such it was, said, "Who are you?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I am Marguerite," the girl said. "And you?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Dr. Johann Faust, at your service."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Marguerite blinked t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
wice, and it was on her mind to say that he couldn't be Faust because the real Faust had just abandoned her to go off joyriding with a demon. But a moment's reflection convinced her that this line of talk might not be a good idea, since this fellow presum
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
bly had rescue in mind, and might not care to be contradicted so vehemently at the very beginning of their relationship. Let him be Faust, or Schmaust, or Gnaust, or whatever he pleased, so long as he got her out of here.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What are you doing here?" Mack as\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That's a long story," Marguerite said. "I was with this other fellow, and, well, he sort of went off and left me here. And you?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack had come to the prison cell in pursuit of Henry Dandolo, hoping to get from him the icon of St. Basil, because this,\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 it seemed to him, was very much what he needed to bring this situation to a successful conclusion. When he reached the first cell he saw that Dandolo, along with blind old Isaac, had left. He was about to leave himself, when some presentiment made him lo
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
k into the next cell. It was strange: it was not his usual way, to look into cells. But this time it had seemed quite urgent that he do so. And so he had done it. But how to tell all this to Marguerite?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Mine's a long story, too," he told her. "Do you want\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  to get out of here?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Does a pig like to wallow?" Marguerite said, using an old expression which was common in the part of Germany where she had been a goosegirl.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Come, then," Mack said. "Stick with me. I have to find somebody."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 They left the dungeon and\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 went out into the camp. It was a scene of confusion and riot. A thousand torches flared, illuminating people scurrying back and forth. Trumpets were blasting, and most people were moving in the direction of the city walls. It seemed that an attack was in
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 progress.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Mack and Marguerite made their way through the crowd, walking in the direction most of the people were going. Everybody was hurrying toward the walls of Constantinople, and it seemed there was fighting going on there. Bloodied men were being help
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ed back from the fray, many of them stuck with Byzantine arrows, which could be distinguished from others by the red and green hexagonal patterns painted on their shafts, and by their feathers, which were of Muscovy duck rather than English goose.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Other so\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ldiers pushed past them to get into the fight. There were signs of struggle on the high battlements. But below, with a sudden clang, the great gates that guarded Constantinople swung open, unbolted by Frankish sympathizers within the city. The mounted Cru
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
aders, seeing this, quickly formed up and galloped toward the open gates in an armored wedge. There were Greek soldiers barring the entrance, and there were Northmen, too, who had been enlisted to fight in the city's armies. They tried vainly to stem the 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ide. But the maddened Crusaders slammed into them, battle-axes and maces swept through the air in short, sharp arcs, and there were cruel sounds as, with terrible effect, they landed on bodies. A group of Greek women atop the wall had brought up a huge ca
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ldron of boiling oil. They tipped it over now, and it came down in a sizzling gold en cascade. Frankish soldiers caught in the flood screamed as the hot oil poured over their armor and came through the neck and arm openings, to broil them inside like so m
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ny lobsters. Then a flight of arrows swept the women away, and the Frankish host was charging again, shouting their battle cries and advancing into the city with irresistible force. A small group of Turkish mercenaries were now the only ones left guarding
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
the inner keep. Their arrows flew hard and fast, darkening the sky, making conversation difficult with the ominous hiss of their passage. Rank after rank of Crusaders were thrown down, rolling away from horses that bristled like porcupines as the Turkish 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rrow storm struck home. Then the tide of maddened Franks reached the ranks of the Turks, who, small of stature and lightly armored, could not stand up to the big, hairy, unshaven European men in their heavy mail. There was a great lopping of limbs and bea
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ing in of heads, and the blood-maddened Franks burst through the Turkish lines into the city streets.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack raced through just behind the fighting, pulling Marguerite along by the hand. Finally he spied Henry Dandolo. The old man was on foot and clutching a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
n enormous sword. He was waving it around so that everybody near him had to duck out of the way. "Lead me to them!" Dandolo was shouting. "Let me at those Greeks!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack ran up, ducking under the sword, and, clutching Dandolo's arm, said, "Henry, it's me, F\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 aust! Let me guide you!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Ah, the messenger from Green Beard!" Dandolo said. "Yes, fine, just point me in the direction of the enemy and give me a push."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'll do that," Mack said, and turned Henry around so that he faced the city walk. As he did so, he de\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ftly removed Dandolo's silken sling, from which he had seen, peeking, the icon of St. Basil.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Best of luck, sir!" he called out, and Henry Dandolo waved his sword and went charging into the battle, a precursor of Don Quixote if there ever was one.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack tur\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ned to Marguerite. "All right, let's get out of here!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack, with Marguerite in tow, now turned away from the city walls and made his way back into the camp. He was in search of a place of safety. One thing he knew for sure was, he had fulfilled his first 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 test. He had made a choice, had saved the icon of St. Basil.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Already it was late. Darkness suddenly fell. The night had turned quite chilly. A cold wind was blowing. Rain was falling. Shivering, shaking, Mack and Marguerite slogged across the muddy battlef\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ield.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Where are we going?" Marguerite asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "There's somebody I have to meet," Mack said, wondering where in hell Mephistopheles was.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Did he say where?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "He said he'd find me."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Then why are we running like this?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We're getting away from the battle. Yo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 u could get killed out there!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 And then they ran into a group of soldiers. These were not the same soldiers who had arrested Faust earlier. These looked quite similar, though, being large and unshaven and hairy and foul-spoken and loaded down with weapons.
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 These fellows had been doing some fighting and they looked all the worse for it. They were beaten and bruised and their armor was dented. They were crouched over a pile of logs and a couple of chairs they had plucked from a passing caravan, trying to get
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a fire going. Over and over they struck flint and steel, but the rain, which had begun just past sunset, was coming down harder and they were meeting with no success.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Hey there, you! Stop a moment!" a voice cried as Mack and Marguerite came up. "Haven't g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ot a bit of dry firewood on you, have you?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "No, no," Mack said. "Sorry, but we don't have any. Excuse us, fellows, we have to go."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The soldiers crowded around them. Marguerite felt something lumpy press against her side. She was about to slap somebody's f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ace when she realized that Mack was trying to get her to take a small sack he had taken from Henry Dandolo. She concealed it on her person as the soldiers grabbed Mack.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 They searched him roughly, and then turned to her. Marguerite, fearing rude hands on he\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r person, dumbly handed over the sack.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Aha!" one of them cried in a triumphant voice, taking out the icon of St. Basil. "What have we here?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Careful with that," Mack said, "that's a special holy icon."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What does it do?" the soldier asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It works mira\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 cles," Mack said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Works miracles, does it? Let's see if it'll start this fire. }{\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 That}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 would be a miracle!" He struck flint and steel. Sparks flew. One of them caught in the varnish on the icon's painted face. The icon sprang immediately into flames.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The sol\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 diers bent down over it, trying to get the burning icon under the other logs. Mack took the opportunity to get away, followed by Marguerite.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 They reached the edge of a little woods that bordered the battlefield. Loud lamentations could be heard from the di\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rection of the city, now that the hiss of arrows had ended. The Crusaders were running wild. Already a pall of smoke hung in the clear moonlit air. It looked like it was going to be Troy all over again.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack looked away. A flash of lightning revealed a tal\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l, sinister figure standing not ten feet from him, wrapped in a crimson cloak, picturesquely posed at the margin of the woods.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Mephistopheles!" Mack cried. "Am I glad to see you!" He hurried up to him. "Did you see what I did? I took the icon option."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Ye\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s, I saw," Mephistopheles said. "Frankly, I'm not impressed."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You're not? But it seemed the best choice. When I heard of Henry Dandolo speak about his plans for the future of Constantinople, I knew that I shouldn't kill him. As for Alexius, I never did ge\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
t close enough to him to kidnap him even if I'd wanted to."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Fool!" Mephistopheles said. "Henry Dandolo was deceiving you. His hatred of Constantinople is implacable."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "How in hell was I supposed to know that?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Read his lips," Mephistopheles s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
aid. "If you had killed him, a better emperor might have been found, who could have saved the city from the terrible sacking and burning that the Crusaders are giving it even now."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I did the best I could," Mack said sullenly.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I don't really mean to scold\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  you," Mephistopheles said. "As I said, it's not you yourself being judged, it's mankind as exemplified by you. You made just the sort of silly choice a human }{
\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 would}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  make. To try to save an illusion rather than perform a practicality!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, I'll do better\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  at it next time," Mack said. "I won't try to save any more illusions, I can tell you that. What's next?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Your second adventure awaits you," Mephistopheles said. "Are you ready?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I could use a bath and a night's sleep."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You will be able to get those thi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ngs at your next stop. You are going to the court of Kublai Khan."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What am I going there for?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I will explain when we get there. Prepare yourself."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Wait!" Mack cried, for Marguerite was tugging at his sleeve. "Can I take her along?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mephistopheles looke\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d at Marguerite, seemed about to refuse, then shrugged. "Oh, I suppose so. Hold hands, close your eyes, and the thing will be done."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack and Marguerite did as they were told. Marguerite also held her breath, because she hated the dizzying sensation of bei\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ng conjured to another place and time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mephistopheles made hand gestures, there was the familiar flash of fire and curl of smoke. And they were gone.
