\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 M}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ack was aware of a strangeness in the outer corridors as he followed Wong, a servant who had been assigned to lead him to hi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
s quarters. He noted how Wong's lantern flame would suddenly sway when there was no breeze to stir it. As they moved through the silent hallways and corridors they came to one that was roped off with a crimson cord.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And what is down there?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "T\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hat is the spirit wing," Wong said. "It is dedicated to the spirits of dead poets. Entrance to it is forbidden to the living. Only the Khan himself and the servants of the Arts may go through with the sacrifices."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What sacrifices?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Brightly colored stone\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s, seashells, moss, and other things that are pleasing to the spirits of dead storytellers."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Wong told him that there were few monarchs as hospitable as Kublai Khan, and none as desirous of hearing the converse of strangers. Kublai was different from other\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 Mongols in the pleasure he took at travelers' tales. He encouraged people from all over the world to come call on him, tell him where they were from and what the customs were like there. He liked to hear about their families, too, and the more extended, 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 he better. And
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Kublai had a whole wing of his palace put aside for hospitality to strangers. This wing was arguably the world's first luxury hotel where people were welcome without a reservation and without money. Just a story.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 There were beggars in the Kh\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
an's palace as well as ambassadors. But they were not ordinary beggars. In the Khan's estimation, a beggar was one with an insufficiency of stories. All the beggars in the Khan's palace were persons who, for one reason or another, were or could be conside
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ed storydead. The Khan supported these unfortunates as a public charity.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Not only were there luxurious rooms for travelers, there was also the special wing for the wandering spirits of poets and storytellers. For it was the Khan's belief that the spirits o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
f poets live forever, in a special celestial kingdom that had been constructed for them alone by the Powers That Be. And these spirits sometimes went awandering back to the Earth, for poets draw inspiration from revisiting the scenes of their former trium
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hs and defeats. And in their peregrinations around their old-time countrysides and city streets, sometimes these spirits were susceptible to outside influences. At such times, the Khan believed, a man could perform a certain ritual, lay out certain offeri
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
gs, and these would attract such spirits, and they would come to the Khan's palace, for they knew they were welcome. Once there, they would find all the things that a spirit might crave: bits of soft fur, shiny shards of mirror, pieces of amber, antique s
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
lver coins, curiously colored pebbles. These were some of the things that were said to give pleasure to the spirits of dead poets, and the Khan had collected many of them. These were laid out in the chambers where the spirits were invited to visit. Incens
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 was burned around the clock in these chambers, and candles were kept lit. And sometimes, a spirit would come to such a place, enjoy the feast of memory that had been laid out for him, and, when he left, deposit a dream in the Khan's head as a gift.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Due to\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 this, the Khan had many remarkable dreams, for he had been visited by spirits telling of savage white whales, of conspiracies in the Roman forum, of great armies moving across a frozen white landscape. He had dreamed of journeying through a dark wood, go
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e from the path direct. He had dreamed of choosing between a lady and a tiger. Thus the Khan piled up a treasure of stories and dreams by day and by night, until he no longer knew which was which, and he worked on his own secret dream, which was to be an 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 udience for dead poets after he had left this life.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack's apartment was of a luxury rarely encountered in the West. And the Khan had thought up many niceties. The servants who fetched him food and drink and hot water for his bath were trained to act as if
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 he weren't there, so that their gaze would not intrude on his inner solitude. Mack found all this very nice, but he could not enjoy it properly for worrying about getting on with his choices. After all, he wasn't a sightseer. He was there to work.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 To do s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
omething with and about Marco Polo seemed a good place to begin. Saving Marco Polo's life ought to be quite a Good Thing. In any event, he could see no harm in it. Nobody gets angry at you for saving their life. Whereas finding a new husband for Princess 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 I\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rene seemed a little risky, and besides, he hadn't even met the princess yet. As for taking Kublai's scepter, it hadn't escaped Mack's attention that there were Mongol bowmen always near the Khan, arrow on bowstring, and whenever anyone even made a gestur
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  in the Khan's direction, the bowmen stiffened and half drew their shafts. It was apparent that nobody got close to Kublai Khan. He'd risk being transfixed by arrows if he tried.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 And then there was Marco Polo to consider.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Tell me," Mack said to Wong, "doe\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s Marco Polo live anywhere around here?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "He keeps an apartment in this complex," Wong said. "But he also has several fine mansions in the city and numerous farms, pleasure domes, and the like elsewhere."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I didn't ask for his real estate holdings," Mack s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 aid. "I merely want to know where to find him."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Right now he's in the Main Banquet Room, supervising the decorating for a great banquet tonight in the Khan's honor."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Be so good as to take me there."
