\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack found himself walking on a road that ran straight between rows of poplars. He topped a little rise and saw, in the near distance, the spires of a noble city. The weather was warm and sunny. There were other p
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
eople strolling along the road. They wore hose, tunics, soft boots, just like in Cracow, but with an Italian panache. Mack saw that Mephistopheles had dressed him in the same way. He proceeded through the gates into the bustling wonder that was Florence.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 T\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
here was a lot of stir and turmoil in the narrow streets. Everybody seemed to be out, most of them in holiday clothing. Florence was in festive mood on this fine spring day. There were multicolored banners snapping in the breeze, flying bravely from many 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
alconies and rooftops. They represented the various communes of the city. Food vendors were out in force, selling the newest taste sensation, tiny Renaissance pizzas. Armed riders in steel helmets coursed through the streets, pushing people out of the way
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
in the manner of policemen of all times and ages. Mack passed close-packed stalk selling cloth, kitchenware, spices, swords, and knives. One stall had large porcelain plates for sale, another watermelon, a third, smelts.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 As interesting as it all was, Mack \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
decided he'd better find a place to stay. First he checked his purse and found that he had plenty of expense money. Mephistopheles had not been stingy in that regard. An inn just up the street appealed to him with its well-painted pastel walls and gold-le
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
f sign proclaiming it the Paradiso. The owner, a stout, red-faced man with a carbuncle on his nose, was suspicious at first, since Mack hadn't sent a messenger ahead to announce his arrival. But he became all affability when Mack handed him a gold florin.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Our best room for you, my dear Dr. Faust! You come at an auspicious time. This is a public holiday, you know, the time when we Florentines burn our vanities."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Yes, I know," Mack said. "Will it be held far from here?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Just a couple of streets away in the\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 Piazza Signoria," the innkeeper said. "You'll have a great view of one of the most remarkable phenomena of our time. Savonarola has promised that this year's bonfire will be something truly remarkable."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What sort of man is this Savonarola?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
He is a most holy monk and friar. He lives simply, unlike the princes of the Church who lord it over us. He speaks out against simony, indulgences, and other bad practices in the Church. And he's in favor of the French alliance."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What's that?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It's our p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 act with the French king, which keeps us protected from the Pope's desire to force the Medicis back on us."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You don't like these Medicis?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Oh, they do well enough," the landlord said. "Lorenzo is called the Magnificent, for good reason. There\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 has never been a greater patron of the arts. Under his rule, Florence has become the most beautiful city in the world."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But you still don't like him?" Mack asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The landlord shrugged. "It's the people who pay for his magnificence. And besides, we don't\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  like any family lording it over us. We Florentines are free people, and we intend to stay that way."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack inspected his room and found it was up to the standard he was rapidly getting used to. Time to find Marguerite. The owner told him that the silk mark\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
et was held in a small piazza on the Fiesole road. To Mack it looked like an oriental bazaar with its stalls crowded close together, its casual bathroom facilities, and its pig-tailed retinue of observers from Cathay. Here were piled high the watered silk
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 that were de rigueur in Flanders and the Netherlands; the twice-dyed material that was making such a hit that year in Amsterdam, and the raw silk estofados and open-necked sanbenito sport shirts for the Spanish trade. Spotted here and there among the sta
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ls were little espresso bars, and near them were spaghetti houses, already selling the concoction that Marco Polo had brought back from China, where they unaccountably called it noodles. Mack found Marguerite at a progenitor of the boutique system that wa
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 to make such a change in the habits of luxury buyers. She was looking at herself in a tall mirror that was tilted this way and that for her by the proprietor, a small man with a harelip but, perhaps in compensation, very good teeth.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Ah, signore," he said\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , "you have come just in time to see your lady in all her glory!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack smiled indulgently. It was not his money. He could afford to be generous.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Go for it, babe," he said huskily.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Look," she said, "I've picked out these darling ball gowns. You must look \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 at Signore Enrico's men's store, Johann. He carries the latest in doublets and camicia."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Camicia?" said Mack.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Signore Enrico smiled with extreme twinklings of his warm brown eyes. "It is the latest thing from Hungary," he said. "A casual style. For evenin\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
g wear we have the most divine tights, which come with a codpiece that whispers masculinity rather than shouting it to the skies."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I just love the way he talks," Marguerite said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Mack felt more than a little foolish trying to respond to this conversation.\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 But he consoled himself by remembering that buying expensive clothes for a beautiful woman is one of the delights of masculine success. And as soon as Marguerite was finished, he could start looking for some stuff for himself, perhaps asking Mephistophel
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
s for an advance on his reward, if need be. Of course, Mephistopheles hadn't specifically mentioned what his reward would be. Mack knew he should have pinned it down earlier. But as soon as he had a chance, he'd check it out. In the meantime, taking a for
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 taste of his reward seemed only reasonable, because if he didn't like what he was going to get he was really wasting his time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You look beautiful, my dear," he said. "Please finish your business so I can get on with mine."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And what business is that, my l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ove?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I need to find a Botticelli. I can make a very good deal if I find one."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Enrico said, "A Botticelli? Perhaps I can help. I know all the painters. It would give me great pleasure to offer my assistance, and, of course, my expertise. Not," he added qu\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ickly, "that I think it will be needed. Because the signore is obviously a connoisseur."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Good idea," Mack said. "Let's check it out now."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 He turned to go. Just then a heavyset man in nondescript clothing burst in.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I am looking for Faust! The German docto\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r! They said at the Paradise that he had come this way!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I am he whom you seek," Mack said. "What seems to be the trouble, my good fellow?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It's my master! He's dying! When he heard there was a new German doctor in town, he sent me out to find him. Oh, s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ir, if you can cure him, you can name your own reward."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'm a little busy," Mack said, not wishing to put his imaginary healing skills to the test, especially in an excitable place like Florence. "Who did you say your master is?'
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "My master is Lorenzo de'\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  Medici, the Magnificent!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Things seem to be falling into shape rather rapidly," Mack remarked to Marguerite. "Come, my dear, pack up your things and wait for me at the hotel. I have an errand of mercy to run."
