ving a body. He scorned the way everyone just lay around Hades all the time, complaining about conditions and talking about the good old days on Earth. He himself wouldn't stoop to complain. Show a little spirit, he told them. Stay in condition. Even thou
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
h the dead aren't able to build muscle, Odysseus exercised faithfully. "You have to retain the ability to do things," he told dead people who asked about this, "even if what you do makes no difference."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Odysseus was sitting on the front porch of his house \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
when Achilles came to ask his help. Odysseus lived by himself in a marble house near a tributary of the Styx. Asphodel grew in the moss on his front lawn. The place was shaded with the inevitable black poplars, which one gets very tired of after a while, 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
n Hades and elsewhere. It was a gloomy day, like all the other days in Hades. It was just chilly enough so you weren't comfortable sitting outside, but not cold enough to be invigorating. Odysseus had a fire going in the living room, but it threw very lit
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
le heat. Not that it mattered: the dead can never get warmed up properly anyway. Odysseus brought Achilles into the kitchen and offered him a breakfast of dates and porridge. They weren't real food, of course. But the dead are attached to the habits of th
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  living and go right on eating, and even plan elaborate banquets. Eternity goes on for a very long time, and food is a way of passing it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Sex is a way of passing time, too, even though dead people can't be properly said to have sex, ectoplasm being devoid \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
of sensation as well as immaterial. But sex is something they used to do, so they go on doing it after death, or at least going through the motions.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Odysseus was currently unmarried. He and Penelope had split up long ago. Odysseus had always had his suspic\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ions about what she'd really been up to with the suitors during the twenty years he was away fighting Trojans. For a while he kept the family together for the sake of the boy, Telemachus. But then Telemachus found his own archetype, nothing big, but quite
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 steady, and now he lived in another section of Hades and had as his friends the sons of other famous men.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 So Odysseus was alone, and he had little to occupy him. He did his exercises faithfully every day. Sometimes he visited his friend Sisyphus. Sisyphus \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
was still rolling the big boulder up the mountain. He didn't have to do it. He had been set free long ago. But, as he said, it gave him something to do, and, above all, it kept his archetype alive.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Sometimes Odysseus went to visit Prometheus, one of his ol\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
dest friends, who was still spread-eagled on a rock, with a vulture eating away his liver. Prometheus had been a difficult case for the gods. Setting him loose would have endangered everybody, since the world still wasn't ready for personal freedom. And t
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e guy wouldn't promise to shut up about his ideas. Again, a modus vivendi, so to speak, might have been worked out\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 sooner or later, all of the dead compromise their values
\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but Prometheus was interested in keeping up his reputation. Recently he had turned \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
oody and some days wouldn't even talk to Odysseus. People said that his only friend was his vulture.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 So Odysseus was bored. He used to go out hunting ghost deer with Achilles or Orion, but that sport soon palled. The main disadvantage of a ghost deer was t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
hat you couldn't kill it. And even if you could, you couldn't eat it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Odysseus was in a receptive mood when Achilles came over and told his problems. Odysseus suggested that they go at once and talk to Dis, king of Tartaros, in the black palace he shared w\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ith Persephone.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Dis had his own problems. He was engaged in jurisdictional disputes with the Roman chthonic deity Plutus, who had recently become the chief deity of the Roman underworld, and had pulled strings to be declared a separate deity in his own rig
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ht and not subsumed under the Hades concept. Because of this ruling, Dis immediately lost control of a large section of the classical underworld, and no longer had jurisdiction over the Latins who had formerly been his subjects. In one way he was glad to 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ee them go. Latin dead had never gotten along well with the Greeks. On the other hand, losing the Latins diminished his kingdom, and shrank his archetype.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 And he was engaged in other jurisdictional battles, because there were always claims from other under\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
world constructs who proposed that Hellenic Hades should be subsumed under them. The gods of the Sanskrit-speaking people had put together a lot of material to show that all the Greek gods originally had come under their aegis, and should do so again. So 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ar, Dis had been able to stave off any final vote on it. But it was still a touchy matter.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Problems, problems. And then suddenly there were Achilles and Odysseus, demanding justice.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "What do you expect me to do about it?" Dis said. "I don't have any power \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 up there. To hell with Dis, that's what they say. They've got new constructs."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "There must be something you can do," Achilles said. "If you're so ineffectual, you should step down and let somebody else rule Hades. I've got a good mind to bring it before th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e Hellenic General Assembly at the next Bylaws of Hades meeting."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Hell, no, don't do that," Dis said. "Let me think about this. Do you know who took her?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "There was "a demon involved," Achilles said. "Alecto told me that. He was one of those spirits from\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the cycle that came after ours."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Which side is this demon on?" Odysseus asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Alecto said he represented Darkness or Badness," Achilles said. "I can't remember which."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Darkness," Odysseus mused. "I suppose that equates with Badness? In that case we kn\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ow which party to apply to for redress. I've never been able to understand the distinctions between Good and Bad. People only started making them some centuries after our time."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Beats the hell out of me too," Dis said. "But people seem to like the Good an\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d Bad stuff."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Odysseus said, "Meanwhile, there's a wrong here we must right. If you'll give us a provisional reality card so we can get out of here, and your authority to act for the classical infernal construct in this matter, Achilles and I will bring th
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 is matter to the attention of the proper authorities."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "All right, you've got it," Dis said. He felt pleased with himself. One of the most important things about having authority is being able to delegate responsibility. Now it was up to Odysseus to right 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 this wrong.
