\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
fter Odysseus received permission from Dis to accompany Achilles to the world of the living, he decided to seek out Tiresias, the most notable magician of the ancient world. Tiresias would know what they had to do and how they coul
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d get where they were going.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 First the heroes had to prepare a blood sacrifice, because Tiresias wouldn't do anything without blood. He was hopelessly addicted to the stuff. Blood was always in short supply in Tartaros, but Dis felt it his duty to supply a
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  skinful from his private store. (It is not true that you can't drink well in Hades, but you have to know somebody.)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The two heroes set off for the grove of Persephone, with its black poplars and aged willows, at the point where two rivers of Hades, Phlege\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
thon and Cocytus, flowed into the Acheron. There they dug a trench and poured in the blood, heroically desisting from drinking it themselves. Whenever dead people came by asking for some, they turned them down. They wouldn't even give a sip to Agamemnon, 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 heir old commander-in'chief, who drifted by, drawn by the scent. This blood was for Tiresias alone.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Dark and oily, the blood lay in the trench. Then it suddenly frothed, then diminished, drunk by an unseen presence. Immediately after that Tiresias appeared\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
, a slight figure in a long gray wool mantle, his face painted with ochre and blue clay, his dank white hair hanging down over his eyes.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "A very good day to you, gentlemen. Thank you very much for the nice sacrifice. Some of Dis' private store, isn't it? L\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ovely stuff! Don't have any more, do you? Too bad! Well then, what can I do for you?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We seek Helen of Troy," Odysseus said. "She has been unlawfully abducted from her husband, Achilles, here."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Somebody always seems to be stealing the fair Helen," Tiresi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 as said. "Do you know who did it?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We are told it was a demon from the new age," Odysseus said. "But we do not know his name or where to find him. We need your advice and assistance."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "All right," Tiresias said. "The demon's name is Azzie and he is part o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 f the new Dark-Light overview which has captured the minds of mankind."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We will go seek him out!" Achilles said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You're going to find it a different world out there," Tiresias said. "You will have to go to the main place from which Evil is commanded, whi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ch is called Hell, and make your enquiries there. I can provide you with a Traveling Spell, as long as you have Dis' permission to use it. As a matter of fact, I happen to know who Helen is with at present."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Tell us!" cried Achilles.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Tiresias cleared his \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 throat and turned toward the trench, now drained of blood.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We have no more to give you," Odysseus said. "But at the first chance we will provide another sacrifice."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "The word of Odysseus is good enough for me," Tiresias said. "But I warn you, finding Hele\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n won't be easy. She's moving around a lot since she is now the consort of a famous magician named Faust."

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Faust?" Achilles said. "That doesn't sound like a Greek to me."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "He's not. Other races have come up in the world and are now the physical as well as\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  intellectual masters. This Faust is engaged in a game with the gods themselves. I mean the new gods."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Where }{\cs17\i\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 are}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  our old gods, by the way?" Odysseus asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "They've been pretty much subsumed under different names," Tiresias said. "They've taken on new ide\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ntities. Most of them don't even remember Greece and Olympus. Except for Hermes, of course, who is still active as the Trismegistus."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well then, where do we find Faust and Helen?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "They are traveling," Tiresias said. "But not only on the Earth. They are t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 raveling in time as well."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Can we get to where they are by boat?" Achilles asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Not unless it's an enchanted boat. Traveling by spell is really the only way."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "You're sure we can't get there by land?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Not that way, either. It takes a bit of magic to g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
et where Helen has gone to. Luckily, I have brought along my bag of spells." From beneath his mantle he took a horsehide bag. It bulged and creaked suspiciously, and gave off little sighs and whines.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "The spells are restless today," Tiresias said. "Use the\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
m with care and mind your fingers when you take them out of the sack. Do not be precipitate. Remember, the matter must proceed step by step. First you have to visit Hell and get permission from the Powers of Darkness to take Helen back. There's always a p
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ocedure in these matters."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "And will you accompany us there?" Achilles asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "No, I will not. But I'll be looking around for information. Don't forget, you owe me a sacrifice! Now, I must away."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Odysseus would have liked something a little more definite. \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
But Tiresias had said his last word. So Odysseus agreed. Tiresias vanished. Odysseus reached into the horsehide bag and separated one spell from where it lay coiled around the others. He brought it out and hastily tied up the sack again. The spell writhed
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
and squirmed, but Odysseus held it firmly and muttered the necessary words. The spell quivered, and then gave a mighty lunge. Odysseus held on, and Achilles held on to him. With classical simplicity, and no baroque nonsense about fire and brimstone, Odyss
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 us and Achilles found themselves in the anteroom of the Kingdom of Dark.
