\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 T}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 he door to Belial's office burst open. Belial gave a jump of startlement. The fat, toad-bodied demon with the blue-gray complexion and the bulging orange eyes had been ga
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
zing into a mirror of illusion, lost in contemplation of his own cleverness and beauty, since in hell self-love replaces self-respect, and he hadn't heard the knock. In strode two brawny figures in pleated white kilts and tunics.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Who are you people?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 m Odysseus," Odysseus said, "and this is Achilles."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Oh. Really?" Belial peered at them closely and saw that they had the classical Greek look\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
big men with straight noses and curly brown hair. Even dead and without a vestige of reality about them, they wer\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e impressive. Some awed clerk at a lower gateway to the realm of Darkness must have issued them a pass of temporary reality. Otherwise they could not have ventured into this place. The inhabitants of the classic underworld had been judged unreal. In the e
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d, it was the only way to get rid of them, and even that didn't work all of the time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Achilles and Odysseus," Belial said. "I've heard about you, of course, but I never expected to actually see you."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "They don't let us out of Tartaros," Odysseus said. "We\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 were too strong for them once. Now they won't permit us any manifestation except the archetypal one, which doesn't affect us anyway except in the form of publicity."
