in his years of working at the Witches' Kitchen. But this was the first time this flabby, sloe-eyed, former citizen of Gehenna had seen two Greek heroes straight out of Homer come walking into his beauty salon. The demon knew at once who they were, becaus
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  he had been a classical scholar before becoming doorman to an afterlife beautification service.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We never had any Greek heroes in before," he muttered. "Do you spirits have a certificate of reality?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Odysseus showed the certificate of temporary reality wh\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ich Dis had given them. The senior witch put down her branding iron and came over and looked at the certificate, and at the passes Belial had given the heroes.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 She said, "It's all right, Tony, let them in."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In the corporealizing treatment that followed, th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e big question was how much heroic musculature to give them. The witches decided not to go in too heavy for bulk, since speed and agility were necessary in most demigodlike pursuits.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Several hours later, Achilles and Odysseus finished the beauty treatment \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
that made them men again. They had used another spell from Odysseus' horsehide bag to take them back to Earth. They were resting under a tree now, not entirely sure of their exact whereabouts. But that didn't worry them. They had brought several days' pro
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 v\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
isions with them from the Witches' Kitchen. At least, it should have lasted for several days. But overcome by the novelty of corporeal food again, they had devoured it all for lunch. After dreaming about food for all those centuries, they hadn't known whe
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  to stop.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'm full," Achilles said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Me too," Odysseus said, "This is one day in which the wise Odysseus didn't eat too wisely. The pickled herring was delicious, though, wasn't it?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I preferred the pate," Achilles said. "I think chopped liver is probabl\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
y the greatest discovery of the world since our time. Remember how it used to be back in classical times? We always had to eat our liver grilled, with onions on the side. There wasn't even soy sauce in those days. Odysseus, how did we stand it?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "We didn't\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  know any better," Odysseus told him. "It would be hard to go back to the Trojan War and army provisions now, though, wouldn't it? Not that there's any chance."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I suppose not," Achilles said. "That was a good war, wasn't it, Odysseus?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "The best," Odysseu\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s said. "There'll never be another like it. Remember when I defeated Ajax?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I never got to see it," Achilles said. "I was already dead then, remember? You were fighting him for my armor."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Yes, and I won," Odysseus said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It was a really great suit of arm\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
or," Achilles said wistfully. "With armor like that it was hard to lose. Wearing it I killed Cycnus and Troilus. But my greatest hit, of course, the one I'll always be known for in the record books, was killing Hector."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I know all about it," Odysseus told\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 "I was just reminiscing. It was later that Paris got me with that sneaky arrow shot\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  In the heel, yet! Oh, well." He sighed and rubbed his belly. "That pate\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 Odysseus, about these bodies we have now\'85\loch\f0 "
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Yes?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "They're supposed to be good ones, aren't \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 they?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Yes, as I understand it, the best."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Well, I've got this pain right down here."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 He pointed to his abdomen.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That's nothing," Odysseus said. "It's a little muscle pull, or, more likely, overeating."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Are you sure it doesn't mean there's something wr\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ong with me?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "They said these were sound bodies. You've had muscle pulls before."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I don't remember ever getting anything like this before. And my feet hurt."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "That's because we've been running. Feet get sore when you run on them. Even when you walk on th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 em."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Achilles said, "Is this how it felt, back when we had bodies?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I suppose it is," Odysseus said. "But we made much less of it then. We were in training. We were accustomed to the joys and sorrows of having bodies."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I don't mean to complain," Achilles\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  said. "I'm stuffed, but I'm hungry again, too. And there doesn't seem to be anything to drink around here."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It's lucky there's not some chronicler around, listening to you," Odysseus said. "Imagine the great Achilles complaining about hunger and thirst!"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I must have said and felt those things back when we were living."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I don't remember you ever admitting you were hungry, Achilles. Mere food was beneath you. Your entire being was dedicated to glory."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "It still is," Achilles said, standing up, wincing. "I\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  think I'm developing a low back pain. Never mind, come on, let's go."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "I'm quite ready," Odysseus said. "But the thing is, I don't know where we should go."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Achilles looked around. He saw they were in a sunny meadow. There was a forest ahead, dark and ver\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
dant. Small birds flew overhead, singing their songs. A light breeze was blowing, and it had a fine clean scent about it. It was just past midday. The sun, now high in the sky, was golden and fine, warm but not hot. It was one of the better days either ma
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  could remember in a long time, and very unlike the typical days in Hades, where it is always on the verge of raining and the skies are the color of a really nasty bruise.
