\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 A}{\insrsid13440386 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 zzie was strolling through the outer courts of the Palace of Justice when he came across Michelangelo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 himself. He recognized the painter from pictures he'd seen of him in art books at Demon U. Michelangelo was just putting the finishing touches on a gigantic fresco.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Looks good," Azzie said, moving behind the painter.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Would you mind getting out of my lig\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ht?" Michelangelo said. "The working conditions are bad enough here without you making them worse."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Azzie moved. "It must be wonderful to create art."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Michelangelo sneered and wiped his sweaty forehead with a paint rag. "This isn't art. I'm just doing some\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  touch-up on an old piece of mine."
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "But you could do original painting if you wanted to, couldn't you?" Azzie asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 "Sure. But in order to paint, a man must aspire, and what is there to aspire to after you've reached Heaven?"
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Azzie had no answer because \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 he'd never thought about it. Michelangelo returned to his work, and, watching him for a moment, Azzie thought he looked perfectly content.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Outside the great auditorium, in the circular corridors that surrounded the circular building, innumerable spirits we\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
re standing around, drinks in hand, eating hors d'oeuvres and talking. There were more spirits here than the place could hold, in fact, because every aethereal, indeed, the greater part of all sentient beings, had wanted to attend. The front office had co
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e up with some new packing orders in an attempt to accommodate all. Even so, the concept of virtual space had had to be invoked, to the distaste of the purists who felt that either you're there or you're not there.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 This was the big day, Judgment Day, the b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
iggest event of the Millennium, the super Mardi Gras of the universe. It was time for everyone to get together with everyone else. Groups of spirits kept on arriving, looking around with awe at the Palace of Justice, then exclaiming, "Gee, so this is the 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
lace!" And then going on to somewhere else, usually the cafeteria, where for the most part they ordered light salads, because they didn't want to lose their appetite for the orgy that was promised if Bad won, or the feast that would be presented if the vi
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 tor was Good.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
All this noise and excitement was a change for Limbo. Limbo was usually a quiet place without anything much happening in the way of entertainment. The inhabitants of Limbo didn't expect much and were willing to live and let live. They tended 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
not to make value judgments, since that was the sole stock in trade of the two adjoining principalities of Dark and Light. The Limboans sauntered along in their strange vague milieu, eating occasional absent-minded meals, making love in their inadequate w
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 y, having mediocre poetry readings and folk dance festivals of no great merit. Time was so eventless here that nobody bothered to keep it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The lack of seasons also contributed to the monotony. And now all of a sudden they were hosting the contest of the Mi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 llennium. It just went to show you could never tell.
